[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on care-journey complexity, channel mix, model choice, integration depth, and human-care-manager backstop overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is a Tuesday afternoon. Maria is 62. Maria has stage-3 breast cancer that was diagnosed six weeks ago, type 2 diabetes that has been reasonably well-controlled for the past nine years, hypertension that is currently not well-controlled because the diuretic interacted badly with the chemotherapy regimen and got swapped out, and a chronic right-knee pain that flares whenever she walks more than about a quarter of a mile. Maria is, as of this Tuesday, four weeks into her treatment plan. Her oncology team has scheduled a port placement for next Monday, the first chemotherapy infusion for the Thursday after that, a baseline cardiac echocardiogram for the day before the infusion (because the chemo regimen is cardiotoxic and a baseline left-ventricular ejection fraction is required), a genetic-counseling appointment because of the family-history pattern, a referral to a breast surgeon for a treatment-planning conversation about post-chemo surgery, a referral to physical therapy for the lymphedema-prevention exercises that her oncology nurse-navigator mentioned, and a referral to a dietitian because Maria has lost six pounds in the four weeks since the diagnosis and her oncology team is concerned about the trajectory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria's primary care physician is, separately, trying to manage Maria's diabetes through the chemotherapy. The PCP has ordered a hemoglobin A1c at the lab affiliated with the PCP's practice (which is on the other side of town from the cancer center). The PCP has also said, in their last visit, that the recent BP readings are not great and has asked Maria to do home blood-pressure monitoring twice a day for the next month. The PCP's office has sent a printed home-BP log, which Maria has not been filling out because she keeps forgetting and the log is on the kitchen counter, which is not where Maria measures her blood pressure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria's endocrinologist (separate from the PCP, separate from the oncologist, in a third health system across two networks) has scheduled a six-month follow-up that happens to fall on the same day as the cardiac echocardiogram. Maria does not yet know about the conflict. Maria's ophthalmologist (annual diabetic-retinopathy screening) sent a reminder card last week that has not been opened. Maria's dentist (the chemotherapy regimen requires a dental clearance before the infusion to rule out active infection) has not been notified that Maria needs an urgent dental appointment in the next week. Maria's pharmacist (chain pharmacy, third location) has refilled the metformin twice without realizing the patient is now on a new chemotherapy regimen with two specialty oncology medications she will pick up at the cancer center's specialty pharmacy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria's husband is also her main support person. Her husband is also working full-time at a job where he cannot easily take time off for medical appointments. Maria's adult daughter lives across the country and calls every evening to ask what is happening, in a tone that is supportive but also (because the daughter is anxious and cannot be physically present) requires Maria to spend forty-five minutes each evening summarizing the day's medical activities for the daughter. Maria's nurse-navigator at the cancer center has called twice this week and Maria has not been able to answer because Maria was at the lab the first time and at her own work the second time. Maria's nurse-navigator has voicemail. Maria has not yet listened to either voicemail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The week's open items, as Maria experiences them, are not a list. They are a low-grade hum of forgotten appointments, missed calls, half-read explanations of benefits, three printed maps to three different parking garages, two copays that Maria's secondary insurance was supposed to cover but apparently did not, and a constant background fear that something important will be missed in the gap between the oncologist and the PCP and the endocrinologist and the breast surgeon and the dietitian and the physical therapist and the genetic counselor and the dentist and the ophthalmologist and the pharmacist and the chemotherapy nurse and the home-BP-monitoring program and the lymphedema-prevention program. The fear is not unreasonable. About a third of the time, in care like this, something important does get missed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria's daughter, on the phone, asks the question Maria has heard from many people in many situations: "isn't there an app for this?" There are a number of apps, in fact. Maria's cancer center has an app, which Maria has installed and uses for messages to the oncology team. Maria's PCP's health system has an app, which Maria has installed and uses for primary-care messages and lab results. Maria's secondary insurance has an app, which Maria has not installed because she could not figure out the activation code. Maria's pharmacy has an app, which Maria uses for refills. None of these apps know about the others. None of these apps know about Maria's daughter. None of these apps know about the dentist, who is not in any of the four networks. None of these apps can tell Maria that Monday's port placement and Tuesday's lab and Wednesday's echo and Thursday's chemo are all sequenced for a reason and what would happen if she tried to move the lab. Maria has, instead, a paper notebook in which she is keeping track of all of this with a pen.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria is, in healthcare-system terms, a high-touch patient. There are many millions of Maria-shaped patients in the United States, and the count is growing as the population ages and as more people accumulate multiple chronic conditions and as cancer survivors live longer in survivorship. <!-- TODO: verify; the prevalence of multimorbidity in adults rises substantially with age, with the majority of older adults having at least two chronic conditions; specific figures vary by source and definition --> The system is not, on the whole, designed for Maria. The system is designed around episodes of care attached to individual specialties, individual encounters, and individual billing events. The work of stitching the episodes together into a coherent care journey, of remembering that the echo is a prerequisite for the chemo and that the dental clearance has to happen before the infusion and that the home-BP log was not optional and that the daughter needs an update, falls almost entirely on Maria. Or, more precisely, on Maria's family, on Maria's nurse-navigator (when she can reach Maria), on the case manager that the secondary insurance assigned (whom Maria has not yet met), and on Maria's ability to keep all of this in her head while undergoing treatment for a serious illness.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, in healthcare-system jargon, is the work of making this work. Care-coordination programs exist in most major health systems, in most major insurance plans, and as standalone services from a growing number of vendors. Care-coordination programs employ care managers, nurse-navigators, social workers, and (in the more sophisticated programs) community-health workers and patient navigators with lived-experience training. The evidence base for care coordination, particularly for high-utilizer and high-acuity patient populations, is meaningful for some outcomes (reduced hospitalization rate, reduced ED utilization, improved preventive-care completion, improved patient experience). <!-- TODO: verify; the care-coordination evidence base includes a substantial body of randomized and quasi-experimental studies showing variable effects on hospitalization, cost, and patient experience, with the strongest evidence in transitional-care and chronic-disease settings --> The economics work for the right patient populations and the right program design. The bottleneck has always been the same one: care managers cost money, care managers are clinically scarce, care managers spend a substantial fraction of their time on tasks that are coordination-shaped rather than clinical-judgment-shaped, and most patients who could benefit from care coordination do not receive it because the workforce is sized for the highest-acuity sliver of the population.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about the conversational AI piece of a care-coordination workflow. The bot is not the care coordinator. The care coordinator is a licensed (or appropriately certified) human, employed or contracted by the institution, who is responsible for the patient's care plan and is the human who actually owns the relationship with the patient. The bot is a structured-task delivery vehicle and an information-routing surface that lets the care coordinator's available time go further: the bot reminds Maria about the home-BP log, surfaces the schedule conflict between the endocrinology follow-up and the cardiac echo, prompts Maria to listen to the nurse-navigator's voicemail, helps Maria find an in-network dentist with availability this week, generates a summary Maria can text her daughter, and keeps a running, single-source-of-truth view of where Maria is in the care journey across all of the providers, plans, and tasks. When the bot encounters something that requires clinical judgment, social-work judgment, or a phone call that the bot cannot make, the bot routes to the human care coordinator with the conversation context attached. The bot is the long-tail of the care-coordination workforce; the care manager is the short-tail of clinical and operational expertise.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that lives alongside an active care-management or care-coordination program, with a defined patient population, a defined care-coordination protocol, a defined human care-manager workforce, integration with the institution's care-management platform of record, and a defined scope. The bot is a structured tool for the routine touches of the program and a routing surface for the clinical and operational touches that need a human.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a freestanding "patient navigator chatbot" that operates without a human care-manager workforce backing it up. Care-coordination work, especially for the high-acuity patients who benefit most, is fundamentally human work. A bot deployed without a sized care-manager workforce is not a care-coordination assistant; it is a checklist-delivery app that may help engaged patients but will not move the outcomes the program is designed to move.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a clinical-decision-making system. The bot does not decide which appointments are clinically required, does not decide which referrals to issue, does not decide medication adjustments, and does not decide whether a patient's symptoms warrant escalation. The bot retrieves information, surfaces tasks, prompts the patient about open items, generates draft messages, and routes to the care manager when the situation requires clinical or operational judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a single-condition tool. Care coordination is, by definition, multi-condition and multi-provider work. The bot's value is concentrated in the patients with multiple active conditions, multiple care teams, multiple care plans, and multiple open tasks. A single-condition bot (cancer-only, diabetes-only) is a different product; it is closer to the chronic-disease coach (recipe 11.7) than to the care-coordination assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. Different patient populations (oncology survivors, complex-medical multimorbidity, post-discharge transitional care, perinatal care, pediatric complex care, geriatric frailty, complex behavioral-health-plus-medical comorbidity, social-determinant-driven complexity) need different content libraries, different escalation thresholds, different care-manager-workforce skill mixes, and different success metrics. Most institutional deployments target a specific population segment, with the architectural pattern shared across deployments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters and years. The integration with the institution's care-management platform, the EHR, the scheduling systems, the patient-engagement infrastructure, the social-determinants-of-health resource networks, and the external-organization integrations (payer plans, community organizations, dental and vision networks not in the institution's primary care-delivery network) is multi-quarter for each integration. The workflow design with care managers and the change-management is multi-quarter on its own. Outcome demonstration is multi-year.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing software in care coordination is generally not in the FDA SaMD-regulated category (the bot is not making clinical decisions and is not delivering therapeutic claims), but the operational, privacy, and patient-safety considerations are substantial. The compliance posture covers HIPAA, state-specific privacy and care-coordination regulations, payer-specific care-management regulatory frameworks (for example, NCQA accreditation requirements that apply to many care-management programs), and (where applicable) accreditation-body requirements (URAC, NCQA, others). <!-- TODO: verify; care-management regulatory frameworks include NCQA care-management accreditation, URAC standards for various care-management roles, and CMS-specific requirements for Medicare and Medicaid care-management programs; specific requirements vary by program type and state -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in the cleverness of its conversational responses. The value is in three places: the durable, single-source-of-truth view of the patient's care journey across all of the providers and plans (a view that does not exist anywhere else in healthcare for most patients), the consistency and reach of the routine-touch coverage (the bot remembers everything; the bot does not forget; the bot works at 11 PM on a Sunday), and the warm-handoff infrastructure that gets the patient to the human care manager when the situation calls for it. A bot evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. A bot evaluated on care-plan-task completion rates, on appointment-attendance rates, on time-to-warm-handoff for clinically relevant disclosures, on care-manager time freed up for clinical work, and on longitudinal outcome trajectories (preventive-care-completion, hospitalization-rate, ED-rate, treatment-adherence, patient experience) is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Care Coordination Grounded In a Multi-Source Care-Plan View, With Warm Handoff to Licensed Care Managers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Software, and Why The Latest Attempts Are Different
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination has been a known unmet need in U.S. healthcare for at least three decades, and dedicated software for it has existed for at least two. The reason previous generations of care-coordination software did not fundamentally move the needle is structural, not technical. The work of care coordination decomposes into three rough categories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first category is information assembly. The care manager spends a substantial fraction of their time pulling together information from the EHR, from the scheduling system, from the patient-engagement platform, from external-organization records (specialty pharmacy, durable-medical-equipment vendor, home-health agency, payer-eligibility system), from the patient's self-reported status, from the patient's family, and from previous care-coordination notes. Every patient touch starts with the care manager assembling the picture. This work is repetitive, labor-intensive, and not the work the care manager is uniquely equipped to do.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second category is task execution. The care manager schedules appointments (or reminds the patient to schedule them, or coordinates between scheduling systems that do not talk to each other), follows up on referrals (or chases the referrals that have not been scheduled, or escalates the referrals that have been declined), confirms benefit eligibility (or works with the payer to authorize the next service), arranges transportation (or social-determinants resources), and closes care gaps (the preventive-care visits, the screening tests, the immunizations the patient is overdue for). This work is repetitive, is labor-intensive, has a high coordination cost per minute of care-manager time, and is mostly not the work the care manager is uniquely equipped to do.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The third category is clinical and operational judgment. The care manager makes calls about whether a symptom warrants escalation, whether a missed appointment indicates a deteriorating trajectory, whether a patient's social situation has changed in a way that requires a social-work consult, whether a care plan needs revision, whether the patient is appropriate for the program at all, whether to have a difficult conversation with the patient about adherence, and so on. This work is what the care manager is uniquely equipped to do.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of care-coordination software (roughly the 2000s) attempted to address category one (information assembly) by building care-management platforms that pulled data from multiple sources into a single care-manager-facing dashboard. This was useful and is now table-stakes; most major care-management platforms do this reasonably well. The platforms did not address categories two and three at all. Category two stayed in the care manager's hands; category three, by definition, has to.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation (roughly the 2010s) attempted to address category two through patient-portal-style tools that let the patient see a checklist of their care-plan items, log their own task completion, and message the care manager. This worked for engaged, motivated, English-speaking, smartphone-comfortable patients who already had the resources and self-efficacy to manage their own care. It did not work for the populations that needed care coordination most. The portal-checklist pattern requires the patient to drive; care coordination, especially for high-acuity populations, requires the system to drive.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that has changed the workflow shape, again, is large language models that can carry on a coherent, sustained, focused conversation. A conversational tool, deployed with careful institutional governance and integrated with the institution's care-management platform of record, can do most of category two (task execution) at scale, can do a meaningful portion of category one (information assembly) on demand for the patient, can recognize when the situation has crossed into category three and route to the human care manager, and can free up the care manager's time for the clinical and operational judgment work that is the manager's actual contribution. The LLM is not the care manager. The LLM is a tool that lets one care manager handle a substantially larger panel without sacrificing the quality of the relationship with each patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "care-management platform that the care manager uses" to "care-management platform plus conversational interface that the patient uses, with the care manager in the loop for the work that requires them." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: the consistency and reach of the routine-touch coverage (a single care manager can, plausibly, support a panel of patients three to five times the size that the care manager alone could support without the bot, depending on patient acuity and program design), the patient-experience improvement (a patient with the bot has a single conversational surface for their care journey, available at any hour, that knows the patient's plan; a patient without the bot has a paper notebook), and the data quality (the bot generates, as a byproduct of its work, a much richer longitudinal record of patient self-report, task completion, and engagement than care managers can collect on their own).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what conversational care-coordination AI is and is not, because the category has been confused by adjacent products. The careful end of the spectrum is bot-as-extension-of-care-manager, with the bot doing structured-task work, information assembly, reminders, scheduling, and warm-handoff to a licensed human for clinical and operational judgment, deployed alongside an active care-management program. The middle of the spectrum is bot-as-checklist-delivery, with the bot reminding patients about plan items but with limited integration and limited handoff. The risky end is bot-as-care-manager, with claims that the bot replaces the human care-manager workforce or reduces the workforce below the level needed for safe operation. This recipe is firmly in the careful end. The architectural decisions are, in part, decisions about which end of the spectrum the product lives on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care-coordination assistant, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active care plan with all of its active goals, tasks, referrals, appointments, and open items; problem list; medication list; recent encounter history; recent self-reported status; recent care-manager notes; patient's stated preferences and care-team relationships; consent posture), access to a structured library of program-specific protocols and patient-education content, and a careful set of tools for retrieving care-plan content, surfacing tasks, scheduling appointments, generating drafts, escalating to care managers, sending messages, and logging events.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is a stream of conversational episodes, sometimes initiated by the patient (most common pattern in mature deployments), sometimes initiated by the bot per a scheduled reminder, sometimes triggered by an upstream event (referral status change, appointment confirmation, lab result release with patient-action implications), sometimes triggered by a care-manager event (manager requests a between-visit check-in).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding into the care-coordination program.** The patient is enrolled in the program through the institution's care-management workflow (care-manager initiated, payer-initiated, or patient-initiated where the program supports it), with documented consent for the program and for the bot interaction specifically. The first conversation introduces the bot, walks through the patient's active care plan in a conversational form, identifies the immediate open tasks, asks about preferences (preferred name, language, channels, quiet hours, communication frequency), and confirms the relationship with the patient's named human care manager.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-plan view and task surfacing.** The patient can ask, at any time, "what do I need to do this week" or "what's coming up" or "do I have anything overdue" and the bot retrieves the active care-plan content from the institution's care-management platform of record and surfaces it in conversational form. The patient can drill into specific items ("what is the echocardiogram for"), can see prerequisite chains ("the echo has to happen before the chemo"), and can see the human-readable explanations the institutional content library provides for each task.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Task-completion logging.** The patient can log completion of tasks ("I did my home BP this morning, it was 142 over 88"), the bot writes to the appropriate longitudinal store, the bot acknowledges the completion, and the bot decides whether the task and result warrant any follow-up (the BP reading above triggers a check on the home-BP-monitoring protocol's escalation thresholds).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Appointment management.** The patient can ask the bot to check upcoming appointments, to confirm or reschedule existing appointments (handing off to the appointment-scheduling bot pattern from recipe 11.2 for the actual scheduling), to identify schedule conflicts (the bot recognizes the endocrinology and echo conflict), to find appointment slots that fit the patient's stated availability, and to add new appointments arising from new referrals.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral tracking.** The patient can ask about the status of a referral, the bot retrieves the status from the institution's referral-tracking system, the bot can prompt the patient to schedule the referred visit, and the bot can route to the care manager when a referral is delayed beyond an institutionally-defined threshold or has been declined and needs alternative arrangement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-gap closure.** The patient can be prompted by the bot, per institutional protocol, to close open care gaps (preventive-care visits, screening tests, immunizations, vaccinations, condition-specific tests like the diabetic-retinopathy screening). The bot uses the standard quality-measure data sources (HEDIS gaps, institutional quality dashboards, condition-specific-protocol tracking) to identify open gaps.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Information assembly on demand.** The patient can ask the bot for a summary of the care journey, for a list of upcoming appointments, for a list of all of the patient's medications, for a list of providers in the patient's care team, for the patient's recent lab results in plain language, or for a specific question's answer ("what was my A1c at the last visit"). The bot retrieves and summarizes from the underlying systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-question answering grounded in institutional content.** The patient can ask questions about their conditions, their medications, what to expect from upcoming procedures, dietary considerations, post-procedure recovery, and so on. The bot answers from the institution's reviewed patient-education content library with citations; the bot routes anything outside the library to the care manager or the appropriate clinician.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Symptom-and-status check-ins per protocol.** Per protocol (oncology check-in template, post-surgical check-in template, post-discharge check-in template, perinatal check-in template), the bot can ask structured questions about how the patient is doing, log the responses, recognize trajectories that warrant escalation, and route to the care manager when escalation criteria are met. This is closer to the chronic-disease coach pattern (recipe 11.7) and reuses much of that pattern's discipline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family- and caregiver-facing support (with patient consent).** Where the patient has designated a caregiver and consented to caregiver participation, the bot can support the caregiver with summaries, reminders, and information appropriate to the caregiver's role. The patient controls what is shared and with whom.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants-of-health screening and resource navigation.** Per protocol and per program design, the bot can administer SDOH-screening instruments (typically the CMS Accountable Health Communities screening tool or institutional-equivalent), surface relevant community resources (food insecurity, transportation, housing instability, financial assistance), and route to the care-management social worker when complex needs are identified. <!-- TODO: verify; the CMS Accountable Health Communities Health-Related Social Needs Screening Tool is widely used and in the public domain; institutional adaptations vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-manager warm handoff.** The bot routes to the patient's named human care manager (or the on-duty care manager when the named one is unavailable) when the situation calls for it: any clinical-symptom escalation, any care-plan question requiring clinical or operational judgment, any patient request for a human, any ambiguous referral or appointment situation, any high-acuity event (deterioration, missed-care-plan-item beyond threshold, social-situation change). The handoff is warm: full conversation context, no patient-restart, bridge-and-stay-present pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-bot integration with the rest of the chapter 11 surface.** The care-coordination assistant is the orchestrator-level bot for high-touch patients; it routes specific tasks to the focused bots (scheduling to recipe 11.2, refills to recipe 11.3, intake to recipe 11.4, benefits to recipe 11.5, triage to recipe 11.6, condition-specific coaching to recipe 11.7, mental-health support to recipe 11.8). The patient experiences a single conversational surface; the underlying architecture has multiple bots collaborating.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-plan-update reflection.** When the patient's care plan is updated by their care team (new referral, changed medication, revised goal), the bot surfaces the change to the patient on next interaction, with appropriate framing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Notification and reminder orchestration.** The bot orchestrates, per patient preference, reminders for upcoming appointments, prerequisite-check tasks (the dental clearance before chemo), care-gap items, and protocol-driven check-ins. The orchestration respects the patient's quiet hours, channel preferences, and the institutional do-not-contact policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding when appropriate.** Patients leave care-coordination programs (program completion, change in eligibility, patient request, transition to a different program). The bot supports the transition with a structured summary delivery to the patient and the care team, plus a clear off-ramp.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, prompt it with "you are a helpful care-coordination assistant," and let it engage with patients about their care journey. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no source of truth for the care plan.** Without integration with the institution's care-management platform of record, the EHR, the scheduling system, the referral-tracking system, the patient-engagement platform, the quality-measure data source, and the relevant external systems (specialty pharmacy, payer-eligibility, community-resource networks), the bot is making up a care plan from the conversation alone. A care-coordination assistant that does not have the actual care plan is, structurally, not a care-coordination assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-source consistency.** The patient's care plan exists in multiple systems with different update cadences, different sources of truth, and occasional inconsistencies. The endocrinology appointment is in the endocrinologist's scheduling system; the cardiac echo is in the cancer center's scheduling system; the dental appointment is in a third system the institution does not own. The bot needs explicit logic about which source is authoritative for which class of data, and what to do when the sources conflict.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of prerequisite chains.** The cardiac echo is a prerequisite for the chemotherapy infusion. The dental clearance is a prerequisite for the chemotherapy infusion. The lab is on a specific cadence. The genetic counseling visit needs to happen before the surgical-planning conversation if the genetic results affect the surgical decision. The prerequisite logic is institutional and condition-specific; the LLM does not know it without explicit grounding.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of what the care manager owns.** Some questions are bot-scope; some are care-manager-scope; some are clinician-scope. The boundaries are institutional. Without explicit scope rules, a generalist LLM tries to be helpful and crosses scope boundaries (a generalist will, when asked about a symptom, attempt to interpret it; the care-coordination assistant routes the symptom question to the care manager or the triage bot).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of program-specific protocols.** Oncology care coordination has different protocols, different thresholds, and different escalation criteria than perinatal care coordination, post-discharge transitional care, or geriatric complex-care management. The bot's behavior is program-specific; the protocols are institutional content the LLM delivers from, not freestyles.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of social-determinants screening.** SDOH screening uses validated instruments (the CMS AHC tool, the PRAPARE tool, institutional-equivalent), with specific question wording, specific scoring, and specific routing rules per institutional protocol. The LLM does this poorly without explicit grounding.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consent.** Care coordination involves multiple parties (the patient, the patient's family, the care manager, the care team, external organizations). What can be shared with whom is governed by the patient's consent, by HIPAA, and by program-specific consent-language. The bot enforces consent explicitly; the LLM does not without explicit grounding.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of escalation thresholds.** A missed appointment is not always an escalation. A missed appointment in a post-discharge patient within the first week is. A blood-pressure reading of 160/100 in a patient on home-BP monitoring per the protocol may or may not be escalation, depending on the protocol thresholds, the trajectory, the patient's history, and the program design. The bot delivers the protocol's escalation rules; the LLM does not without explicit grounding.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the patient is in clinical or social emergency.** When the patient discloses symptoms suggesting emergency (chest pain, sudden weakness, severe shortness of breath, suicidal ideation, intimate-partner violence with safety implications), the response is not "let me help you process this." The response is to surface the appropriate emergency resources, route to the care manager, and (where appropriate) cross-route to the triage bot or the mental-health support bot. The crisis-pathway logic is encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-bot orchestration.** The care-coordination assistant routes specific tasks to specific specialist bots (scheduling, refills, intake, benefits, triage, chronic-disease coaching, mental-health support). The orchestration is multi-bot; a single generalist LLM trying to do all of it loses scope discipline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule arithmetic problems.** SDOH screening scoring, care-gap-identification logic, quality-measure-status computation, and related arithmetic on structured inputs are deterministic computations. The LLM does these poorly. The deterministic rule tools encapsulate the computations; the LLM gathers inputs and presents results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to care coordination.** Care-coordination programs are subject to specific accreditation standards (NCQA care-management accreditation, URAC standards, CMS Medicare-and-Medicaid care-management requirements, and (in some payer contexts) HEDIS and HEDIS-adjacent measures with care-coordination-specific specifications). <!-- TODO: verify; care-management accreditation and quality-measure frameworks are documented by NCQA, URAC, CMS, and others; specific requirements vary --> The audit, retention, documentation, and reporting requirements vary by program type and by accrediting body.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-source data synchronization.** The patient's appointment in the cancer-center scheduling system, the endocrinologist's scheduling system, and the dentist's scheduling system are managed independently. The bot's view of "your appointments this week" is a join across sources, with read-through-cache discipline, source-of-truth annotation, and conflict resolution. The LLM does not synchronize across sources; the data layer does, and the LLM presents the result.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has companion-pattern risk.** A care-coordination assistant in extended interaction with a high-touch patient over months can drift into companion-pattern territory ("I've been thinking about you, Maria"). The bot is warm but boundaried; the system prompt and output safety enforce non-companion framing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Care Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking, companion-pattern avoidance, warm handoff to licensed humans. The care-coordination assistant adds seven structural commitments those recipes did not have at the same prominence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-source care-plan-of-record integration as architectural primitive.** The bot's view of the patient's care plan is a synthesized view across the EHR, the care-management platform, the scheduling systems (potentially multiple), the referral-tracking system, the quality-measure data source, the patient-engagement platform, and the relevant external systems. Each source has a defined role, a defined update cadence, a defined source-of-truth boundary, and a defined conflict-resolution rule. The synthesized view is a first-class data product, not a runtime concatenation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-bot orchestration and routing.** The care-coordination assistant is the orchestrator for high-touch patients across the chapter 11 bot surface. The orchestration includes context handoff to specialist bots, return-from-specialist-bot handling, conversation-thread continuity across the patient's experience, and shared longitudinal store maintenance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Program-specific protocol delivery with care-manager-workforce integration.** The bot delivers from program-specific protocols (oncology, perinatal, post-discharge, geriatric, etc.) reviewed and signed off by the program's clinical leadership and care-management leadership. Each program has defined escalation thresholds, defined task templates, defined check-in cadences, and defined care-manager-workflow integration patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-manager workforce integration as primary architectural component.** The bot is deployed alongside an active care-management workforce. The named-care-manager relationship is preserved in the longitudinal store. Warm handoffs route to the named manager (or the on-duty manager when the named one is unavailable) with full context. The care-manager workflow tooling (most often the institution's care-management platform of record) integrates with the bot's tool surface. The deployment is sized so the bot extends the care-manager's reach, not replaces it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **SDOH screening and resource navigation as architectural primitive.** The bot administers institutionally-validated SDOH screening (CMS AHC tool or similar), routes positive screens to the care-management social worker, and surfaces relevant community resources from the institution's curated network.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system task-completion logging and downstream-system reflection.** When the patient logs task completion through the bot, the completion is reflected in the appropriate downstream system (the EHR, the care-management platform, the quality-measure data source, the scheduling system) per institutional integration patterns. The bot is not a parallel data island; it is a write surface into the systems that own the data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-care-team summary generation with consent.** The bot generates summary delivery to multiple care-team members (the PCP, the oncologist, the endocrinologist, the care manager, the social worker), per consent posture, with appropriate scope and framing for each recipient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: input/output safety, citation grounding, scope discipline, persona discipline, prompt-injection defense, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration surface is the largest in the chapter.** Care coordination touches the EHR, the care-management platform, multiple scheduling systems, the referral-tracking system, the patient-engagement platform, the quality-measure data source, the SDOH-resource directory, the secure-messaging surface, the appointment-reminder system, the patient-education content library, the protocol library, the care-manager workflow tooling, the payer-eligibility system, and the external-organization integrations (specialty pharmacy, durable-medical-equipment vendor, home-health agency, community organizations, dental and vision networks not in the primary care-delivery network). Most institutions discover, partway through the project, that the integration work is multi-quarter for each integration, and that the data quality in each integrated system is variable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The care-manager-workforce model is the deployment-readiness gating factor.** A care-coordination assistant deployed without an actively-staffed, named-care-manager workforce, with peak-hour coverage and per-program skill-mix appropriate to the patient population, is not a deployment that will move outcomes. The bot extends the workforce; it does not replace it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient population segmentation drives the architecture.** Oncology survivors, complex-medical-multimorbidity patients, post-discharge transitional-care patients, perinatal-care patients, pediatric complex-care patients, geriatric-frailty patients, complex-behavioral-health-plus-medical-comorbidity patients, and SDOH-driven-complexity patients have different needs, different escalation thresholds, different content libraries, different care-manager-skill-mix requirements, and different success metrics. Most institutions deploy by program, with the architectural pattern shared across programs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Engagement is a function of acuity and program design.** High-acuity patients in well-designed programs engage at high rates because the bot is materially valuable. Lower-acuity patients in less-well-designed programs disengage because the bot is incremental rather than transformative. Engagement targets, by program, are negotiated with operational leadership based on the program's value proposition.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome attribution is harder than for the previous bots.** Care coordination's outcome metrics include hospitalization rate, ED utilization, preventive-care completion, treatment-adherence, patient experience, total cost of care, and (for specific programs) condition-specific metrics. The attribution work is harder than for single-condition bots because the coordination work touches many domains; the analysis is observational and benefits from matched-cohort or quasi-experimental design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The cost economics depend on the program type.** For high-acuity, high-utilizer populations (top 5% of medical-cost-distribution patients), care coordination has well-established value-based-contract and risk-sharing economics. For lower-acuity populations, the economics are more dependent on payer-specific arrangements (CCM/PCM billing under Medicare, care-management-specific contracts with commercial payers, value-based-arrangement-specific care-coordination provisions). The bot's deployment is justified differently in different contexts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are amplified.** Care coordination is, in part, navigating the healthcare system on behalf of the patient. Patients with limited English proficiency, with low health literacy, with cultural differences in family decision-making, with lived experience of healthcare-system inequity, and with social-determinant-driven complexity have different navigation needs. A bot that operates only in English, only references one cultural framework, and only addresses one set of navigation challenges is excluding much of the population that benefits most from care coordination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family and caregiver involvement is structurally different from the other recipes.** In the chronic-disease coach (recipe 11.7) and the mental-health support bot (recipe 11.8), the patient is primarily the participant. In care coordination, the family caregiver is often the secondary participant, with their own consent posture, their own preferred channels, and their own information needs. The bot supports caregiver participation per patient consent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants-of-health work is care-coordination work.** A meaningful fraction of care-coordination effort goes to addressing social-determinant barriers that prevent the patient from completing the medical care plan: transportation, housing stability, food security, financial-assistance, language services, technology access, etc. The bot's SDOH screening and resource-navigation capability is integral to the program, not an add-on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is moderate but specific.** A care-coordination assistant that fails to surface a critical missed appointment, fails to escalate a deterioration signal, or fails to enforce consent in a cross-team summary has specific liability exposure. The institutional malpractice carrier and the institutional legal counsel are part of the policy review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management platform-of-record adoption is mature.** Most major health systems and most major payers operate on a care-management platform (commercial vendors include several mature offerings; some institutions have built or extended in-house). The platform is the system of record for the care plan, the care manager's notes, the program enrollment, and the program metrics. The bot integrates with the platform; the bot is not a parallel platform.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-native care-plan exchange has improved but remains incomplete.** FHIR R4 includes CarePlan, Goal, Task, ServiceRequest, and related resources that are appropriate vehicles for care-plan content. Adoption of these resources for cross-organization care-plan exchange has improved with TEFCA and with payer-specific FHIR exchange requirements but remains uneven. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR R4 CarePlan, Goal, Task, and ServiceRequest resource adoption for care-plan exchange is documented in HL7 implementation guides and in the TEFCA framework; specific adoption varies by organization and use case --> Most current deployments use a hybrid of FHIR-where-available and proprietary-integration-where-required.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **HIE and TEFCA-mediated cross-organization data flow is improving.** The TEFCA framework has expanded the practical reach of cross-organization data exchange, which is materially relevant for care coordination across the patient's full provider network. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation has continued through 2024-2026 with growing QHIN participation and expanding use-case coverage; specific status varies by region --> The bot's care-plan view benefits from improved cross-organization data flow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Quality-measure frameworks (HEDIS, MIPS, CMS Star Ratings) include care-coordination-specific measures.** Many care-coordination-relevant quality measures exist in HEDIS and CMS Star Ratings (medication reconciliation post-discharge, follow-up after ED visit, follow-up after hospitalization, care-plan documentation, transitions-of-care measures, etc.). <!-- TODO: verify; care-coordination-specific quality measures in HEDIS, MIPS, and CMS Star Ratings include specifications for transitions-of-care and care-management activities; specific measures vary by year and program --> The bot's task surfacing prioritizes the patient-action items that affect these measures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Validated SDOH screening tools are well-established.** The CMS Accountable Health Communities Health-Related Social Needs Screening Tool, the PRAPARE (Protocol for Responding to and Assessing Patient Assets, Risks, and Experiences), the Hunger Vital Sign, and several condition-specific or population-specific SDOH instruments are widely used and have published validation. <!-- TODO: verify; the CMS AHC tool and the PRAPARE tool are widely used SDOH screening instruments with published validation literature --> The bot delivers from these instruments per institutional protocol.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-source orchestration well when carefully integrated.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination at higher integration count. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve care-plan content, retrieve scheduling information, retrieve referral-status, log task completion, retrieve SDOH-resource information, escalate to a care manager, send messages, and post events for downstream operations. The integration burden is in the tool implementations, not in the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination products at health-system and payer scale, with care-management platform integration, EHR integration, and (in some cases) integrated care-manager-workforce-as-a-service. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for the care-management platform, the patient-engagement infrastructure, and (where applicable) the care-manager-workforce-as-a-service component.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Workforce-augmentation framing is the dominant institutional posture.** The accepted positioning across major institutional deployments is "the bot extends care-manager reach; it does not replace care-manager judgment." Deployments that have positioned otherwise (workforce-replacement, workforce-elimination) have generally faced clinical, operational, and accreditation pushback. The architectural decisions reflect this framing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity and access disparities are an active concern.** Care-coordination programs have shown variability in adoption, engagement, and outcomes across patient demographics. <!-- TODO: verify; disparities in care-management program engagement and outcomes are documented in published studies of specific programs and populations --> Per-cohort monitoring with explicit equity focus is essential, and SDOH-resource navigation is part of the equity strategy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
